			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="head">
					<marginalia_text>
						Optima Maxima mundi disciplina: scientia omniu[m]
						prudentissima, atq[ue] fortissima industria:
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						cum
						solida temperantia, et amabili a[e]quitate.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Adde necessariu[m] instructum: et
						( vicisti.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Discipline is the best and greatest thing of the world;
				the most prudent wisdom and strongest industriousness of all;
				with a solid temperance and a pleasant fairness.
				Add the instruction of necessary matters and you have won.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						Eccè Ca[e]saris, et Alexandri contentio in Juliani Ca[e]saribus:
						qua[e] mera est Fortitudinis, prudentia[e]q[ue]
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
					<person name="Alexander the Great"/>
					<person name="Julian"/>
					<book title="Caesars"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Comparatio. Qua dignitate alijs visi sunt
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						omnibus pra[e]celluisse. At
						Fortitudo est adhuc fortior: prudentia adhuc prudentior:
						industra deniq[ue] et expeditior; et potentior;
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						et constantior;
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						et ingenti effectu mirabilior. 
						Hic Eutrapeli Scopus.
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Eutrapelus"/>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Sed vanum est maxima cogitare, Sine maiori effectu,
						aut efficaciori probatu. Vnde maximis opus est
						causis: pra[e]sertim arte, virtute, necessarijs instrume[n]tis.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Here is the struggle of Julius Caesar and Alexander in Julian's Caesars,
				which is a comparison of pure strength and prudence, by whose dignity
				they seemed to surpass all other men. But strength is still stronger;
				prudence is still more prudent; and industriousness, finally, is more ready
				and more potent; more constant; and more wondrous with a remarkable effect.
				This is the goal of Eutrapelus.
				But it is vanity to consider the greatest things without the greater effect,
				or the more effective proof; whence it is necessary for the greatest causes,
				especially in art, virtue, and other necessary instruments. 
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="270" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nihil adhuc suprà illa[m] Ca[e]saris, et Alexandri 
						concertationem. Potest esse aliquid Superius: Si no[n] imperio, at dignitate. 
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
					<person name="Alexander the Great"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				Nothing is as yet above that conflict of Julius Caesar and Alexander. Anyone could be greater,
				if not in rule, at least in dignity.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
